analysisWe need to solve Sudoku. Let's denote grid coordinates row1-col1 etc.

We have 9x9 puzzle:

Row1: . 4 . 6 3 . . . .
Row2: . 8 . 1 . 7 . 6 .
Row3: 6 3 . . 8 2 . . 7
Row4: . . . . . 6 7 4 5
Row5: . . . . . . . . .
Row6: 8 2 6 4 . . . . .
Row7: 2 . . 7 5 . . 9 4
Row8: . 1 . 2 . 3 . 7 .
Row9: . . . . 1 4 . 2 .

We need to solve. Let's attempt systematically.

I'll use deduction.

Represent each row as set of missing digits.

Row1: digits present {4,6,3}. Missing {1,2,5,7,8,9}. Col positions:
- c1: column1 has values: r1?, r2?, r3=6, r4?, r5?, r6=8, r7=2, r8?, r9?. So column1 missing {1,3,4,5,7,9}. Intersect with row1 missing {1,2,5,7,8,9} gives {1,5,7,9}. So r1c1 ∈ {1,5,7,9}.
- c3: column3 values: r1?, r2?, r3?, r4?, r5?, r6=6, r7?, r8?, r9?. Missing digits {1,2,3,4,5,7,8,9}. Intersect with row1 missing gives {1,2,5,7,8,9}. 
- c6: column6 values: r1?, r2=7, r3=2, r4=6, r5?, r6?, r7?, r8=3, r9=4. Missing digits {1,5,8,9}. Intersect => {1,5,8,9}.
- c7: column7 values: r1?, r2?, r3?, r4=7, r5?, r6?, r7?, r8?, r9?. Missing {1,2,3,4,5,6,8,9}. Intersect => {1,2,5,8,9}.
- c8: column8 values: r1?, r2=6, r3?, r4=4, r5?, r6?, r7=9, r8=7, r9=2. Missing digits {1,3,5,8}. Intersect => {1,5,8}.
- c9: column9 values: r1?, r2?, r3=7, r4=5, r5?, r6?, r7=4, r8?, r9?. Missing digits {1,2,3,6,8,9}. Intersect => {1,2,8,9}.

Row2: . 8 . 1 . 7 . 6 .
Present {8,1,7,6}. Missing {2,3,4,5,9}. 
- c1 column1 missing {1,3,4,5,7,9}. Intersect => {3,4,5,9}.
- c3 column3 missing {1,2,3,4,5,7,8,9}. => {2,3,4,5,9}.
- c5 column5 values: r1=3, r2?, r3=8, r4?, r5?, r6?, r7=5, r8?, r9=1. Missing digits {2,4,6,7,9}. Intersect => {2,4,9}.
- c7 column7 missing {1,2,3,4,5,6,8,9}. => {2,3,4,5,9}.
- c9 column9 missing {1,2,3,6,8,9}. => {2,3,9}.

Row3: 6 3 . . 8 2 . . 7
Present {6,3,8,2,7}. Missing {1,4,5,9}. 
- c3 column3 missing {1,2,3,4,5,7,8,9} => {1,4,5,9}
- c4 column4 values: r1=6, r2=1, r3?, r4?, r5?, r6=4, r7=7, r8=2, r9?. Missing digits {3,5,8,9}. Intersect => {5,9}
- c7 column7 missing {1,2,3,4,5,6,8,9} => {1,4,5,9}
- c8 column8 missing {1,3,5,8}. => {1,5}

Row4: . . . . . 6 7 4 5
Present {6,7,4,5}. Missing {1,2,3,8,9}. 
- c1 column1 missing {1,3,4,5,7,9} => {1,3,9}
- c2 column2 values: r1=4, r2=8, r3=3, r4?, r5?, r6=2, r7?, r8=1, r9?. Missing digits {5,6,7,9}. Intersect => {9}
So r4c2=9 fixed.
Remaining missing {1,2,3,8}. 
- c3 column3 missing {1,2,3,4,5,7,8,9} => {1,2,3,8}
- c4 column4 missing {3,5,8,9} => {3,8}
- c5 column5 missing {2,4,6,7,9} => {2}
Thus r4c5=2.
Remaining missing {1,3,8}. 
- c1 {1,3,9}->{1,3}
- c3 {1,2,3,8}->{1,3,8}
- c4 {3,8}
Only number 8 appears in c3 or c4. good.

Row5: . . . . . . . . .
All empty. Missing digits {1-9}. We'll fill later.

Row6: 8 2 6 4 . . . . .
Present {8,2,6,4}. Missing {1,3,5,7,9}. 
- c5 column5 missing {2,4,6,7,9} => {7,9}
- c6 column6 missing {1,5,8,9} => {1,5,9}
- c7 column7 missing {1,2,3,4,5,6,8,9} => {1,3,5,9}
- c8 column8 missing {1,3,5,8} => {1,3,5}
- c9 column9 missing {1,2,3,6,8,9} => {1,3,9}

Row7: 2 . . 7 5 . . 9 4
Present {2,7,5,9,4}. Missing {1,3,6,8}. 
- c2 column2 missing {5,6,7,9} => {6}
So r7c2=6.
Remaining {1,3,8}. 
- c3 column3 missing {1,2,3,4,5,7,8,9} => {1,3,8}
- c6 column6 missing {1,5,8,9} => {1,8}
- c7 column7 missing {1,2,3,4,5,6,8,9} => {1,3,8}

Row8: . 1 . 2 . 3 . 7 .
Present {1,2,3,7}. Missing {4,5,6,8,9}. 
- c1 column1 missing {1,3,4,5,7,9} => {4,5,9}
- c3 column3 missing {1,2,3,4,5,7,8,9} => {4,5,8,9}
- c5 column5 missing {2,4,6,7,9} => {4,6,9}
- c7 column7 missing {1,2,3,4,5,6,8,9} => {4,5,6,8,9}
- c9 column9 missing {1,2,3,6,8,9} => {6,8,9}

Row9: . . . . 1 4 . 2 .
Present {1,4,2}. Missing {3,5,6,7,8,9}. 
- c1 column1 missing {1,3,4,5,7,9} => {3,5,7,9
